post_text:
Fayette Schools: LEAPS Grant Awarded for Next Three Years

Fayette County Public Schools was awarded a renewal of the LEAPs Grant. This grant renewal will provide students at East Junior High and Fayette-Ware High School with afterschool enrichment for an additional three years. Students who sign up for the program will receive free academic assistance, social and emotional skills development through clubs, field trips, and community-based programs as well as enhanced creativity and problem-solving skills through STEM. More information will be provided on this exciting program within the coming weeks.

Fayette Schools: LEAPS Grant Awarded for Next Three Years

Fayette County Public Schools was awarded a renewal of the LEAPs Grant. This grant renewal will provide students at East Junior High and Fayette-Ware High School with afterschool enrichment for an additional three years. Students who sign up for the program will receive free academic assistance, social and emotional skills development through clubs, field trips, and community-based programs as well as enhanced creativity and problem-solving skills through STEM. More information will be provided on this exciting program within the coming weeks.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: District Receives Monsanto Grant for Robotics

Last year, East Junior High School received a grant from the Monsanto Fund to improve their STEM lab and purchase much-needed supplies and materials to enhance their STEM program. This year the school was awarded a $15,000 grant to begin a robotics program at the school. Students will learn coding skills and begin participating in competitive robotics with other schools.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Anonymous Donor Helps BCES Secure Supplies

Thanks to a very generous anonymous donation, the teachers at Buckley-Carpenter Elementary will be well-prepared! A check in the amount of $1500.00 was presented to the school to purchase teacher supplies for classrooms. Desiree Bawcum, Chief of School at BCES, said the money will go toward cleaning supplies, hand sanitizer, tissue, Lysol wipes, and other much-needed items for teachers. Our district is grateful for the support of our local churches and various community sponsors.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Wildcats Hold Their Own in FCA Golf Tourney

On Monday, August 31st, the Fayette-Ware boys’ golf team participated in the Fellowship of Christian Athletes’ Annual Golf Tournament held at Windyke Country Club in Memphis. Freshman Sam O’Brien, Junior Kylan Johnson, and Sophomore Nolin Craft put in 18 holes on the Par 3 course. All three Wildcats had a good showing but Nolin Craft medaled in the event with the 2nd lowest score for the day. Coaches Underhill and Duke were pleased with how the boys played.

Fayette Schools: Ongoing Professional Development Adds Value for Teachers

It looks like students are not the only ones being educated! While students have begun the year learning virtually, teachers have continued getting an education as well. Dr. Breeden, Chancellor at Fayette-Ware High School, provided an interactive professional development for her faculty around Canvas, the district’s learning platform. By giving teachers constant feedback and continual instruction, they are able to further assist students in their learning and education.

The Lady Wildcats are off to a great start with their first district win over Ripley 9-0. Already having played two non-district games, the team is now 3-0. Cici Hunter scored an amazing five goals, Kaylie Moody added another two goals and three assists, Sydnei Marshall chipped in another goal, and senior Sarah Sudduth rounded things off with one goal and one assist. Now that’s teamwork!

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Virtual Learning Becomes Hands-On

When most people think of virtual learning, the thought of screen time comes to mind. Although time in front of the computer is involved, teachers across the grade spans have included unique opportunities for hands-on activities that extend the lesson for students. Middle school students have had opportunities to do fun experiments at home and test them for effectiveness while the smallest students in pre-K are using items found at home to create the first letter in their name. Virtual learning can be interactive and fun!

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Wildcats Win Season Opener Against Chester County

In a tight game, the Wildcats pulled out a win against Chester County in the season opener at home. For the first score of the game, quarterback Kyle Lowe took it 32 yards for a touchdown. Unable to follow up with the extra point, the Wildcats led Chester 6-0 with 8 minutes left in the first quarter. Closer to the half, Chester scored their first touchdown, closing the gap to 14-6. A little too close for comfort, quarterback Lowe ran another TD in before the half. Wildcats led 20-6 going into the locker room. Coming out after the break, former Wildcat QB Tony Washington who is now current Chester QB, would not be denied and ran 40 yards for a touchdown to bring the score to 20-12. After a back and forth battle with Fayette trailing at one point, the Wildcats come back strong to beat Chester 36-32. What an exciting first game!

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Schools to Remain Online Until Sept.14th

On August 10, 2020, Fayette County Public Schools opened virtually with students learning online at home and all educators teaching from their classrooms at school. Both teachers and administration have been working diligently with families to assist with student learning and to help families with any problems that may arise. Based on the COVID 19 data for Fayette County, Fayette County Public Schools will continue to teach students online until Monday, September 14, 2020. It is the intent of FCPS to get students back to school in the blended model as quickly as possible, where students are attending school in cohorts two days per week and continuing to learning virtually from home three days a week. Communications will go out weekly to keep the community updated with any new information.

It is the intent of FCPS to get students back to school in the blended model as quickly as possible, where students are attending school in cohorts two days per week and continuing to learning virtually from home three days a week. Communications will go out weekly to keep the community updated with any new information.

FCPS Meal Distribution delivery clarification:

1. Nobody will knock on the door. Drivers will blow the horn when they reach the driveway so someone can meet the driver at the bus to pick up the meals. This can be a parent/guardian or student.
2. Meal distribution time will be from 11-2 daily. Please be listening for the horn.
3. Meals will not be delivered on Friday; however, you can pick up meals at the closest school on Friday from 10:30-12:30.

For further concerns or questions, feel free to contact Lisa Plunk at lisa.plunk@fcsk12.net.

Fayette Schools: Pre-K Still Available Near You!

Although the school year has already begun, we are still accepting applications for pre-K students! The early years teach valuable social skills, problem-solving concepts as well as critical thinking skills. As children learn through exploration, they become creative thinkers and doers. If you are interested in signing your child up for pre-K, call 465-5260 for more information or visit our Central Administration Building located at 10425 Hwy 76 S. in Somerville to register now.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Girls’ Soccer Off to Winning Start

The girls of Fayette-Ware kicked off their soccer season with a win against Fayette Academy. Although this was not the first matchup between these two teams, the Lady Wildcats seemed to have the upper hand and won the match by a score of 3-1. Seniors Cici Hunter and Kaylie Moody scored all three goals for the team, with Cici scoring two and having one assist and Kaylie scoring one and also having an assist. Senior Katie Green had an assist as well. Although the majority of the starting lineup for the Lady Wildcats are seniors, the freshman players stood out as the potential leaders and playmakers of the future.

Senior Katie Green had an assist as well. post_text: The Fayette County School Board approved a request from Head Baseball Coach Brian Young for a new fence at the baseball field. The fence is eight feet tall and will be in royal blue. With the addition of much-needed extra new concrete around the baseball and softball fields, Young states, “Instead of a place where there is just a baseball and softball field, now it’s becoming more of an actual ballpark.” Future plans are an addition of a press box and concession stand, adding to the overall fan experience. Fans are strongly encouraged to come and see the new additions and upgrades while supporting the FCPS athletes.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Dr. Smith Makes School Rounds, Checks on Staff

As any good leader would do, interim superintendent Dr. Connie Smith traveled to every school this week to check the pulse of faculty and staff members as schools began educating students. Moving forward with the district plan, students will be educated virtually until Labor Day and then move into the blended model where students will attend school two days per week and remain virtual three days per week if the COVID data permits. Dr. Smith wants to ensure that all students will be educated in a safe and healthy environment where protocols are in place to protect the students and staff.

Moving forward with the district plan, students will be educated virtually until Labor Day and then move into the blended model where students will attend school two days per week and remain virtual three days per week if the COVID data permits. Dr. Smith wants to ensure that all students will be educated in a safe and healthy environment where protocols are in place to protect the students and staff.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Educators Engage Students, Make Family Connections

As public schools opened safely across Fayette County, teachers went the extra mile to ensure connections were being made with families and students. Although the learning began virtually, that didn’t stop FCPS educators from reaching students. Whether they interacted through Zoom or simply read a live story, it was important to teachers to make the home-school connection and see smiling faces. Student and family participation in virtual learning is vital to student learning and success, so educators must be creative in their teaching to ensure all families are reached.

Fayette Schools: Golfers See First Match of Season

The golf team at Fayette-Ware got into the swing of things as they participated in their first match of the season. The team headed to Woodland Hills Golf and Country Club to play nine holes against Chester County and Jackson Southside. Although this was their first match, it was not considered a district match. Coach Duke led the team of four boys while Coach Andrea Underhill played one girl in this match. The Fayette-Ware golf team has one match per week lined up through the middle of September.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: 6th Annual, 1st Virtual State of the Schools

As schools prepare to begin educating students, the district held its 6th Annual State of the Schools. For the safety of the faculty and staff, this year’s event was held virtually. Although each school staff viewed at their own school site, they were able to watch together and be seen by everyone in the district during the school roll call. The main event was held at the Central Administration Building, and holding with tradition, featured a hilarious opening skit by Dr. Breeden and Dr. Currie. Words of encouragement were spoken by Pastor Stan Smith and School Board Chairman Wendell Wainwright followed by the honoring of the retirees. Dr. Connie Smith led the charge to the schools around school opening and educating students safely. No matter the circumstances, the event will go on!

****TECHNOLOGY DISTRIBUTION!****

IF YOU MET THE August 4 DEADLINE to request a device here’s what you should know:

shared_text:
Fayette Cares
July 28 at 8:03 AM ·

Many homeless families with school-aged children find help at Fayette Cares, which is why Fayette County Public Schools is partnering to equip our shelter with technology including computers, printers, and internet access.

Federal data shows student homelessness is at an all-time high with over 1.5 million children and youth homeless during the 2017-18 school year, an 11% increase over the previous year. Student homelessness in rural America is reported to be growing at nearly 4x the national rate, and we don’t yet know how the pandemic will affect these numbers.

Displaced students face barriers that put their academic achievement at risk. The trauma and instability of homelessness affects mental and physical wellness, increases the likelihood of chronic absenteeism, and often results in negative educational outcomes.

With virtual learning options becoming essential, these important resources will provide the tools children need to succeed in school and beyond.

Fayette County Public Schools

Fayette Schools: Parents, Teachers Engage in Feedback Session Around School Reopening

Gaining feedback from stakeholders is an important step in the decision-making process. FCPS held a Parent-Teacher Focus Group meeting to engage this particular group of stakeholders representing each school in order to gain insight around health and safety topics prior to the board voting on a reopening option. School Board Chairman Wendell Wainwright and additional member Civil Miller-Watkins were on hand to listen to the comments and concerns brought forth during the meeting. The dialogue was authentic and provided many points of feedback for the leadership team.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Community Supports Schools, Provides Essential Resources

The COVID-19 pandemic has changed the way we live our everyday lives and it will certainly alter the way education will look in the future. As Fayette County Public Schools moves forward to prepare for the upcoming year, our community partners have stepped up in a big way to support student and staff health and safety. The Mayor’s Office and the Homebuilder’s Association have both secured 80 thermometers each for use in schools and by the transportation department. These will be a vital component in daily temperature checks to ensure student and staff safety. Four cloth face coverings per student, for the entire 3400 student population, were generously donated by the TN Emergency Management Association per Judi Sipowicz. It is through the substantial support of the community and these agencies that our schools will continue to operate in a safe and sanitary manner.

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Class of 2020 Makes Graduation Official

After a long wait, the class of 2020 finally made their graduation official! On Tuesday, June 16, 2020, the graduates participated in an outdoor ceremony to mark the end of their senior year. Although it seemed this event may not happen, the administrative staff at Fayette-Ware High School worked tirelessly to pull together an amazing ceremony for the students and their families. Even though every family member was not able to attend due to social distancing, the ceremony was live-streamed for the community to view. Memorable speeches were given by the valedictorian, salutatorian, and the senior class president to their classmates, reminiscing of times past and encouraging them to move forward and stay strong. If the resiliency and strength of these seniors are any indications of their future, they will go far.

Memorable speeches were given by the valedictorian, salutatorian, and the senior class president to their classmates, reminiscing of times past and encouraging them to move forward and stay strong. If the resiliency and strength of these seniors are any indications of their future, they will go far.

During a scheduled drive-thru, the seniors circled through the school grounds at 10:00 AM one last time to pick up their graduation packets and celebrate the class of 2020. The school administrative team was on hand to assist with packet pick-up and cheer on the seniors. Congratulations, class of 2020!

post_text:
Fayette Schools: Extraordinary Shake: And the Winner Is…

Each year since 2017, LaGrange-Moscow Elementary has hosted an event called the Extraordinary Shake, which tests students' communication, professionalism, and other soft skills. Due to COVID-19, LaGrange-Moscow Elementary School's annual Extraordinary Shake event went virtual! Students were invited to sign up, and 16 4th and 5th graders accepted the challenge! Round 1 consisted of 60-second video introductions. In Round 2, 10 students debated a topic relating to COVID-19. Round 3 was a gauntlet of challenges in which 7 students
were required to demonstrate customer service, management skills, and persuasion. During Round 4, the top 6 students were asked to create and record a video marketing pitch. During Round 5, three students completed a final interview. A panel of judges scored these students
remotely, and in the end the top three students were recognized: Abigail Styers, 4th grader - 1st place, Elijah Vinson, 5th grader - 2nd place, and Kyla Moore, 5th grader - 3rd place.

Fayette Schools: Schools Celebrate Students at Year’s End

As the school year came to an end, schools celebrated their students even when their doors were closed. Faculty and staff wanted families to know that even though the school year did not end as anticipated, their students remained the top priority. Schools closed out in spectacular fashion, with drive-through ceremonies and end-of-year closeout for students. Vehicles were decorated to commemorate the occasion and the staff at many schools were dressed in a luau theme. This was certainly a time for celebration!

Fayette Schools: Students to Participate in Ron Clark’s Global Amazing Shake

Two former Extraordinary Shake winners from LaGrange-Moscow Elementary will be participating in Ron Clark’s Global Amazing Shake competition. Much like LMES’s local event, the Global Amazing Shake is a competition that places an emphasis on teaching students manners, discipline, respect, and professional conduct but on a much grander scale. This competition will be held online May 18-22, 2020, and these local scholars have already been practicing virtually to prepare. What an incredible experience these students have to experience competition on a global platform!
